(226, 4, 'http://feeds.washingtonpost.com/c/34656/f/636708/s/30e84821/sc/8/l/0L0Swashingtonpost0N0Cworld0Czvonko0Ebusic0Eskyjacker0Ewho0Echampioned0Ecroatian0Eindependence0Edies0Eat0E670C20A130C0A90C0A60Ce0A8d26120E170A30E11e30Ebe6e0Edc6ae8a5b3a80Istory0Bhtml0Dwprss0Frss0Iworld/story01.htm', '2013-09-07 02:16:43', 'Zvonko Busic, skyjacker who championed Croatian independence, dies at 67', 'zvonko,busic,skyjacker,championed,croatian,independence,dies', 'Zvonko Busic, a Croatian nationalist who served 32 years in prison in the United States for hijacking a plane and planting explosives that killed a policeman, has committed suicide. He was 67. Police said Mr. Busic was found dead Sept. 1 at his home in Rovanjska, near the coastal Croatian town of Zadar. They said he left a suicide note. Read full article &amp;#62;&amp;#62;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;', 'zvonko,busic,croatian,nationalist,served,years,prison,united,states,hijacking,plane,planting,explosives,that,killed,policeman,committed,suicide,police,said,found,dead,sept,home,rovanjska,near,coastal,town,zadar,they,left,note,read,full,article,nbsp', '', 'zvonko,busic,skyjacker,championed,croatian,independence,dies,nationalist,served,years,prison,united,states,hijacking,plane,planting,explosives,that,killed,policeman,committed,suicide,police,said,found,dead,sept,home,rovanjska,near,coastal,town,zadar,they,left,note,read,full,article,nbsp', NULL, '2013-09-07 07:54:42'),
(227, 4, 'http://feeds.washingtonpost.com/c/34656/f/636708/s/30e7dbee/sc/20/l/0L0Swashingtonpost0N0Cworld0Ceurope0Cfor0Efrance0Eus0Edelay0Eon0Esyria0Efuels0Edoubts0C20A130C0A90C0A60Ce80A365740E16da0E11e30E961c0Ef22d3aaf19ab0Istory0Bhtml0Dwprss0Frss0Iworld/story01.htm', '2013-09-07 01:09:00', 'For France, U.S. delay on Syria fuels doubts', 'france,delay,syria,fuels,doubts', 'PARIS &mdash; For French President Fran&ccedil;ois Hollande, it seemed like the perfect response: a lightning-quick strike on Syria to punish the government for an alleged chemical weapons attack. But with President Obama&rsquo;s surprise decision to ask Congress for a go-ahead on military action, Hollande has found himself embroiled in political controversy abroad and at home. Instead of vaunting Hollande as a warrior charging off to do battle, critics say he now looks more like a sidekick who was left in the lurch by his American ally. Meanwhile, the possibility of bombing Syria has proved deeply unpopular in French public opinion. Read full article &amp;#62;&amp;#62;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;', 'paris,french,president,fran,hollande,seemed,like,perfect,response,lightning,quick,strike,syria,punish,government,alleged,chemical,weapons,attack,with,obama,surprise,decision,congress,ahead,military,action,found,himself,embroiled,political,controversy,abroad,home,instead,vaunting,warrior,charging,battle,critics,looks,more,sidekick,left,lurch,american,ally,meanwhile,possibility,bombing,proved,deeply,unpopular,public,opinion,read,full,article,nbsp', '', 'france,delay,syria,fuels,doubts,paris,french,president,fran,hollande,seemed,like,perfect,response,lightning,quick,strike,punish,government,alleged,chemical,weapons,attack,with,obama,surprise,decision,congress,ahead,military,action,found,himself,embroiled,political,controversy,abroad,home,instead,vaunting,warrior,charging,battle,critics,looks,more,sidekick,left,lurch,american,ally,meanwhile,possibility,bombing,proved,deeply,unpopular,public,o