(243, 4, 'http://feeds.washingtonpost.com/c/34656/f/636708/s/30d83688/sc/7/l/0L0Swashingtonpost0N0Cblogs0Cblogpost0Cpost0Cthe0Efour0Ereasons0Erussia0Ewont0Egive0Eup0Esyria0Eno0Ematter0Ewhat0Eobama0Edoes0C20A130C0A90C0A50C143397a40E1640A0E11e30E961c0Ef22d3aaf19ab0Iblog0Bhtml0Dwprss0Frss0Iworld/story01.htm', '2013-09-05 19:30:00', 'The four reasons Russia won&rsquo;t give up Syria, no matter what Obama does', 'four,reasons,russia,give,syria,matter,what,obama,does', ' President Obama arrived in Russia today for the Group of 20 economic summit, where everyone is hoping he might be able to make some progress with Russian President Vladimir Putin over Syria. But Obama will not actually be meeting with Putin -- they had planned a one-on-one, but the White House canceled it after Russia sheltered NSA leaker Edward Snowden. So the mission to soften Putin&rsquo;s support for Syria, which is a major obstacle to ending the war, would appear to be over before it&rsquo;s begun. Read full article &amp;#62;&amp;#62;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;', 'president,obama,arrived,russia,today,group,economic,summit,where,everyone,hoping,might,able,make,some,progress,with,russian,vladimir,putin,over,syria,will,actually,meeting,they,planned,white,house,canceled,after,sheltered,leaker,edward,snowden,mission,soften,support,which,major,obstacle,ending,would,appear,before,begun,read,full,article,nbsp', '', 'four,reasons,russia,give,syria,matter,what,obama,does,president,arrived,today,group,economic,summit,where,everyone,hoping,might,able,make,some,progress,with,russian,vladimir,putin,over,will,actually,meeting,they,planned,white,house,canceled,after,sheltered,leaker,edward,snowden,mission,soften,support,which,major,obstacle,ending,would,appear,before,begun,read,full,article,nbsp', NULL, '2013-09-07 07:54:42'),
(244, 4, 'http://feeds.washingtonpost.com/c/34656/f/636708/s/30d6fcb1/sc/7/l/0L0Swashingtonpost0N0Cblogs0Cblogpost0Cpost0Cthe0Ereal0Ecase0Efor0Esyria0Estrikes0Emakes0Esense0Eso0Ewhy0Eisnt0Eanyone0Emaking0Eit0C20A130C0A90C0A50C7b947cc60E162f0E11e30E961c0Ef22d3aaf19ab0Iblog0Bhtml0Dwprss0Frss0Iworld/story01.htm', '2013-09-05 17:31:38', 'The real case for Syria strikes makes sense, so why isn&rsquo;t anyone making it?', 'real,case,syria,strikes,makes,sense,anyone,making', ' Early last week, when Secretary of State John Kerry made the Obama administration&rsquo;s first public case for limited U.S. strikes against Syria, he was actually quite clear about why: because strikes to punish the Syrian government would uphold the international norm against the use of chemical weapons, which Syrian forces had allegedly deployed against civilians. Students of international relations can and do disagree about whether that would work, but they at least agree that it&rsquo;s a sound and valid case to make, one consistent with everything the administration has said about how the strikes would work and what they would and wouldn&rsquo;t do. Read full article &amp;#62;&amp;#62;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;', 'early,last,week,when,secretary,state,john,kerry,made,obama,administration,first,public,case,limited,strikes,against,syria,actually,quite,clear,about,because,punish,syrian,government,would,uphold,international,norm,chemical,weapons,which,forces,allegedly,deployed,civilians,students,relations,disagree,whether,that,work,they,least,agree,sound,valid,make,consistent,with,everything,said,what,wouldn,read,full,article,nbsp', '', 'real,case,syria,strikes,makes,sense,anyone,making,early,last,week,when,secretary,state,john,kerry,made,obama,administration,first,public,limited,against,actually,quite,clear,about,because,punish,syrian,government,would,uphold,international,norm,chemical,weapons,which,forces,allegedly,deployed,civilians,students,relations,disagree,whether,that,work,they